It appears to me that our discussions are very much effected by affect.  Emotions start us on a direction of discovery but we quickly take a tangent to attack or defend.  We are caught in some type of &quot;Control Issue Rodeo&quot; where we get bucked off only to climb back on again.  We do a lot of good riding... but in no particular direction.  Our particular needs to control have us climbing on a wild bronc to prove that we can do it.  Well, there is some control gained for 8 seconds.<br>
However, instead of gouging the wild bronc with our spurs... lets gain more meaningful controls by breaking the wild bronc to ride.  We need the same amount of courage and resolve.. But let's try patience and persistence.. And above all... seek a goal.<br>
If I were a surgeon and a wounded man lay on the table before me... I would not care Who shot him or Why he was shot or who was shot yesterday or who may get shot tomorrow.  That type of thinking comes later...and does serve a purpose.<br><br>
So much has happened and so quickly.  John mentions chemistry.  Well done John!  Chemistry is where it's at.  Catecholamine...neural transmitters... brain juice... is a type/class  of amine (chemicals) that enable, facilitate or inhibit thinking - feeling, registering the world and reacting to it.  Chug a lug a pint of whiskey... smoke a joint... or eat a hand full of pills and see if your outlook... thinking... behavior doesn't change.  We understand that!  What we fail to realize is that our views or thoughts of a frightening incident..(real or imagined) which has occurred or is anticipated gives us a mental... neurological, chemical bath.  It is possible that we become addicted to mental as well as physical pain.  Endorphins, opium-like substances produced in the brain and pituitary gland are generated by our response to stimuli that make our muscles ache or our souls ache.  We may have an (unknown to us) motive to lay in the quagmire of despair...(self defeating behavior... private pity party.. Etc.)<br><br>
Cook rings a bell!  He is right on with his pondering of Why some do and some don't react to PTSD!!  Bro Barela, like the rest of us may be unconsciously exercising that defense mechanism called &quot;Splitting,&quot; ... Viewing oneself or OTHERS as all good or all bad without integrating positive or negative qualities of the person into the evaluation... seeing all or none... black or white... rather than considering the full range of the continua.  At the expense of my own exaggeration, Bro sees Marines as a tougher group .  FACT: They either are... or they're not!<br>
Where you're coming from may dictate What you see (perceive).  You may be biased...ALL helicopter pilots are tough (because I'm one!)  Could it be that Marine Corps training better prepares one for the horrors of war...Your mind set does impact on how you gather and process information.  I know a lot of Marines and Chopper drivers that have serious and chronic PTSD.  A one ton truck can carry more than a half ton truck.. But that doesn't prevent a one ton truck from being overloaded till its axels break.  Its just a matter of different breaking points.<br>
Other than being a Marine or what ever, it could be that people who remained in the military service defused somewhat... or people who went into some other challenging work like police work... paramedic... etc. never felt the radical difference of going from combat to mundane clean sidewalks.  Could it be that two different people can witness the same event and come away with different feelings or feelings that vary in intensity?  Could it be that some fellows are better at lying to themselves than others? (Numbing.. Denial.. Repressing.. Suppressing!)<br><br>
Still working on &quot;Fear=control issues.&quot;<br>
Mustang Two Four<br><br>
      
